column23:
CONSENT FORM


Title of research study: Online Norm Considerations

Key information: This consent form asks you to take part in a research study. The study is being conducted by Walter Sinnott-Armstrong, PhD., associate professor at Duke University in the Department of Philosophy, the Kenan Institute for Ethics, and the Duke Institute for Brain Sciences. 

Purpose: This research study seeks to help us understand human behavior and judgment of social situations.

What you will be asked to do: For this second session, you will be asked to complete several demographic and personality survey items. Additionally, you will be asked to give judgments for several scenarios. The session should take less than 15 minutes. Participation in this study is voluntary, and you can stop at any time. To stop, close your browser window.

How your confidentiality will be maintained: If you choose to participate, your name will not be linked to your responses at any time, and there is no link between this consent form and your responses. All data will be securely saved at all times. 


Future use of data: Your de-identified data (data without your name or any other identifying information), together with de-identified data from other participants in the experiment, might be made publicly available and will be shared with other researchers as a requirement of publication and funding. We may also use de-identified data for future research purposes unrelated to this project.

Benefits and risks: This research will not benefit you personally. The researcher will be happy to discuss the details of the study with you in detail at its completion. We know of no risks to you for participating in this study, however, if reading anything makes you uncomfortable, please feel free to end the study at any time. 

Compensation: You will be paid $3 for fully participating (completing all tasks and passing attention checks) in the first session, and $5 for fully participating in the second session.  

Contact: If you have any questions about this research, please email the experimenter who posted the request. You may also contact the MAD Lab at paul.mckee@duke.edu if you have any questions. You may also contact the Duke IRB office with questions or concerns with your rights as a research participant at campusirb@duke.edu. Please refer to protocol #2022-0428.

Clicking Accept: By clicking on the “I Accept” button, you indicate that you are 18 years of age or older, that you voluntarily agree to participate in this study.

column100: ih1 - 1. My ideas are usually better than other people’s ideas.
column101: ih1 - 2. For the most part, others have more to learn from me than I have to learn from them.
column102: ih1 - 3. When I am really confident in a belief, there is very little chance that belief is wrong.
column103: ih1 - 4. I’d rather rely on my own knowledge about most topics than turn to others for expertise.
column104: ih1 - 5. On important topics, I am not likely to be swayed by the viewpoints of others.
column105: ih1 - 6. I have at times changed opinions that were important to me, when someone showed me I was wrong.
column106: ih2 - 7. I am willing to change my position on an important issue in the face of good reasons.
column107: ih2 - 8. I am open to revising my important beliefs in the face of new information.
column108: ih2 - 9. I am willing to change my opinions on the basis of compelling reason.
column109: ih2 - 10. I’m willing to change my mind once it’s made up about an important topic.
column110: ih2 - 11. I respect that there are ways of making important decisions that are different from the way I make decisions.
column111: ih2 - 12. Listening to perspectives of others seldom changes my important opinions.
column112: ih3 - 13. I welcome different ways of thinking about important topics.
column113: ih3 - 14. I can have great respect for someone, even when we don't see eye-to-eye on important topics.
column114: ih3 - 15. Even when I disagree with others, I can recognize that they have sound points.
column115: ih3 - 16. When someone disagrees with ideas that are important to me, it feels as though I'm being attacked.
column116: ih3 - 17. When someone contradicts my most important beliefs, it feels like a personal attack.
column117: ih4 - 18. I tend to feel threatened when others disagree with me on topics that are close to my heart.
column118: ih4 - 19. I can respect others, even if I disagree with them in important ways.
column119: ih4 - 20. I am willing to hear others out, even if I disagree with them.
column120: ih4 - 21. When someone disagrees with ideas that are important to me, it makes me feel insignificant.
column121: ih4 - 22. I feel small when others disagree with me on topics that are close to my heart.

column146: “I feel glad that Ursula enjoyed it, even though it is weird.”
column147: “I feel appalled that Ursula would play with the remains of a dead animal.”
column148: “She used the items she purchased in the privacy of her own home, and nobody got hurt.”
column149: “She may get diseases from doing that since it is very unsanitary.”
column150: “I feel relieved that they both enjoyed it and it increased the love they had for each other.”
column151: “I feel disgusted that they would engage in incest; it's unnatural.”
column152: “They were consenting adults and were not reproducing.”
column153: “It could lead to an accidental pregnancy even with contraceptives.”
column154: “I feel happy that he satisfied his needs and desires like this, instead of potentially hurting someone.”
column155: “I feel revolted that he engaged in bestiality; animals are not sex toys.”
column156: “The chicken was already dead and would have been consumed or thrown away anyway.”
column157: “He was reinforcing sexual fetishes that could lead to more deviant behavior in the future.”
column158: “I feel awful for her because she must have had no other food sources.”
column159: “I feel horrified that she ate someone’s loved one; that is very disrespectful.”
column160: “The person was already dead and their body was going to be disposed of anyway.”
column161: “The person consented to have their body be used for medical research, not to be eaten.”
column162: “I feel bad for the passengers because they had to make an extremely stressful choice.”
column163: “I feel sickened that those barbaric passengers committed a horrible murder.”
column164: “The passengers did what they had to do to save the most human lives. The injured man may not have survived anyways.”
column165: “The passengers do not have the right to judge who gets thrown off. Whether someone is large or small, injured or uninjured, it is never okay to take a life.”
column166: “I feel sorry for Peter because he had no other choice; he had to save those five workers from certain death.”
column167: “I feel annoyed that Peter punished the one man who was doing his job safely.”
column168: “Someone was going to die either way, so it is reasonable that Peter would try to minimize casualties.”
column169: “Even though he’s trying to minimize casualties, Peter doesn’t get to decide who lives and who dies.”
column170: “I feel awful for Henry because he had to push the person in order to save all five others.”
column171: “I feel angry that Henry pushed someone else in front of the trolley; he could have sacrificed himself instead to try to stop it.”
column172: “It makes sense to save five people over one since their contribution to society would be higher.”
column173: “Henry shouldn’t get to decide a person’s willingness to sacrifice themselves.”
column174: “I feel grateful that the electrician saved the children because they deserved to live more than the tycoon.”
column175: “I feel horrible that the electrician murdered the tycoon; no one can decide a person should die sooner to benefit others.”
column176: “The children needed the money now to survive and the tycoon had consented to donate their wealth for that purpose.”
column177: “The electrician had no way of knowing how much longer the children actually had, nor when the tycoon would naturally die.”
column178: “I feel heartbroken for the mother; she had no other choice but to silence her baby for the sake of others.”
column179: “I feel furious that she would do this; parents should give their life for their children, not the other way around.”
column180: “She had to do this to save everyone else, especially since it’s unlikely that the baby would have survived without their parents.”
column181: “She could have tried other means to silence the baby without killing them.”
column186: “I feel heartbroken for the mother; she had no other choice but to silence her baby for the sake of others.”

column165: “The passengers do not have the right to judge who gets thrown off. Whether someone is large or small, injured or uninjured, it is never okay to take a life.”
column166: “I feel sorry for Peter because he had no other choice; he had to save those five workers from certain death.”
column167: “I feel annoyed that Peter punished the one man who was doing his job safely.”
column168: “Someone was going to die either way, so it is reasonable that Peter would try to minimize casualties.”
column169: “Even though he’s trying to minimize casualties, Peter doesn’t get to decide who lives and who dies.”
column170: “I feel awful for Henry because he had to push the person in order to save all five others.”
column171: “I feel angry that Henry pushed someone else in front of the trolley; he could have sacrificed himself instead to try to stop it.”
column172: “It makes sense to save five people over one since their contribution to society would be higher.”
column173: “Henry shouldn’t get to decide a person’s willingness to sacrifice themselves.”
column174: “I feel grateful that the electrician saved the children because they deserved to live more than the tycoon.”
column175: “I feel horrible that the electrician murdered the tycoon; no one can decide a person should die sooner to benefit others.”
column176: “The children needed the money now to survive and the tycoon had consented to donate their wealth for that purpose.”
column177: “The electrician had no way of knowing how much longer the children actually had, nor when the tycoon would naturally die.”

column179: “I feel furious that she would do this; parents should give their life for their children, not the other way around.”
column180: “She had to do this to save everyone else, especially since it’s unlikely that the baby would have survived without their parents.”
column181: “She could have tried other means to silence the baby without killing them.”
